  "response": "To simplify the expression \u221a(75yz^2), we can first factor 75 into its prime factors.\n75 = 3 \u00d7 25 = 3 \u00d7 5 \u00d7 5 = 3 \u00d7 5^2\n\nNow, we can rewrite the expression as:\n\u221a(75yz^2) = \u221a(3 \u00d7 5^2 \u00d7 y \u00d7 z^2)\n\nUsing the property \u221a(ab) = \u221aa \u00d7 \u221ab, we can separate the expression:\n\u221a(3 \u00d7 5^2 \u00d7 y \u00d7 z^2) = \u221a3 \u00d7 \u221a(5^2) \u00d7 \u221ay \u00d7 \u221a(z^2)\n\nNow, we can simplify the square roots:\n\u221a3 remains as \u221a3\n\u221a(5^2) = 5\n\u221ay remains as \u221ay\n\u221a(z^2) = |z| (assuming z can be negative, otherwise it would just be z)\n\nCombining these simplified terms, we get:\n\u221a3 \u00d7 5 \u00d7 \u221ay \u00d7 |z| = 5|z|\u221a(3y)\n\nIf we assume that z is non-negative (i.e., z \u2265 0), then |z| = z, and the simplified expression is:\n5z\u221a(3y)\n\nFinal Answer: The final answer is $\\boxed{5z\\sqrt{3y}}$",
